\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have seen how S-patches are transformed into trimmed Bézier
 patches, let us look at some practical issues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Efficiency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Efficient-composition-algorithm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is still computationally demanding.
 Converting an 5-sided S-patch of depth 8 took more than 5 minutes on a
 2.8GHz processor.
 There is a much faster approach – see the upcoming paper of the author.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Salvi:2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Triangles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three-sided S-patches, i.e., Bézier triangles, are converted into simple polynomia
l patches, since computing the barycentric coordinates do not involve rational
 polynomials.
 Note however, that there are alternative methods for the quadrilateral
 transformation of a triangular patch, see e.g.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Warren's domain deformation method.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Warren:1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Control net quality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One issue with the conversion is that the quadrilateral control grid may
 have outlier control points or spikes near the corners.
 This is because the denominator of Wachspress coordinates vanish on a circle
 around the domain, and these singularities undermine the stability of these
 areas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The S-patch representation of multi-sided surfaces can be an important asset
 in the designer's toolbox.
 It can be used to fill holes or create smooth vertex blends, and then it
 can be exported to CAD/CAM systems as a trimmed Bézier patch, without losing
 precision, thus making it possible to create perfectly watertight models.
 In this paper we have reviewed the steps required for the quadrilateral
 conversion, and discussed some related questions.
\end_layout

